<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>RECONDITIONING ROTORS - INSPECTION - WORN ROTORS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="1">
        <title>WORN ROTORS</title>
        <para>The minimum worn rotor thickness is shown on the outside diameter of the rotor braking section or cast
            into the rotor body (
            <hotlnk document="s04018w_4.xml" xrefid="f0401810">Figure 10
                <xref refid="f0401810"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ).
        </para>
        <para>The minimum dimension applies to any cross-sectional measurement across the rotor surfaces in contact with
            the brake pads (Item 1,
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401822">Figure 22
                <xref refid="f0401822"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ). The wear should be approximately equal on both inner and outer braking surfaces (Items 2 and 3,
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401822">Figure 22
                <xref refid="f0401822"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ). If the wear on one braking surface is considerably more than the other (Items 4 and 5,
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401822">Figure 22
                <xref refid="f0401822"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ), the brake is not functioning properly and should be further examined.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0401822" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401822" filename="../figg04/G0401822.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 22. Worn Rotor</caption>
        </figure>
        <para>The rotor may be resurfaced but must never be used if it is below the minimum rotor thickness which is
            cast into the O.D. of the rotor (
            <hotlnk document="s04018w_4.xml" xrefid="f0401810">Figure 10
                <xref refid="f0401810"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ).
        </para>
    </svcproc>
